# Frontend Architecture - Cross-cutting Non-Negotiables

**Audience:** engineers designing, reviewing, or operating browser-facing applications and static sites - regardless of framework (React, Vue, Svelte, Solid, Astro, Next, Nuxt, Gatsby, Hugo, Eleventy, SvelteKit, Remix).

**Scope:** the choices that apply *the same way* across frameworks. For framework-specific advice (React Server Components, Vue Composition API, Hugo partials, etc.), defer to the framework's docs and to `999-local-overrides.mdc` in each consumer repo. This rule is the cross-cutting layer; the skill `frontend-engineering` is the depth.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Frontend rules in this repo are intentionally framework-agnostic. Adding React/Vue/Hugo encyclopedia content here would be shallow guidance authored from docs, not earned from production reviews. Pin framework-specific guidance in `999-local-overrides.mdc` per repo.

---

## Non-negotiables

### NN1. Rendering choice is made before code lands

SPA / SSG / SSR / ISR / hybrid is an architecture decision, not a default. Document it in an ADR or the README before the first feature commit.

| Pattern | When | Trade-off |
|---|---|---|
| **SSG** (static site generation) | Content changes less than daily; SEO matters; no per-user state | Cheapest hosting (CDN-only); rebuild on every change |
| **SSR** (per-request) | Per-user content; SEO matters; freshness matters | Server cost; slower TTFB than SSG if not cached |
| **SPA** (client-side render) | Internal tools; authenticated apps; no SEO need | Worst TTFB / FCP; bad on slow networks; richest interactivity |
| **ISR** (incremental SSG) | Mostly-static with occasional updates | SSG cost + on-demand re-render budget |
| **Hybrid** (RSC, islands, partial hydration) | Mix of above per route | Most complex; biggest payoff at scale |

### NN2. Bundle budget per route is enforced in CI

Every PR runs against a budget. PRs that breach are blocked until either the budget is raised (with justification in the PR description) or the code is trimmed. Raising the budget silently is the same anti-pattern as suppressing a test.

| Route type | Initial JS budget | LCP target |
|---|---|---|
| Marketing / landing | < 100 KB gz | < 1.5s |
| App shell / dashboard | < 200 KB gz | < 2.5s |
| Heavy app route (editor / map / chart) | < 400 KB gz | < 3.0s |

Tooling: Lighthouse CI, `bundlewatch`, `size-limit`, `@next/bundle-analyzer` + CI gate, `rollup-plugin-visualizer` for Vite, `webpack-bundle-analyzer` for legacy stacks.

### NN3. Three buckets for state; never mix

| State class | Where it lives | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| **Local UI state** | `useState` / `ref` / `signal` | Form field value, modal open/closed, hover state |
| **Server state** | TanStack Query / SWR / Apollo / urql / Pinia query | API responses, mutations, cache invalidation, optimistic updates |
| **Global client state** | Zustand / Redux Toolkit / Pinia store / nanostores | Auth user, feature flags, theme, in-flight workflow state |

The most common frontend refactor: server data stuffed into Redux/Zustand with hand-rolled caching, invalidation, refetch-on-focus, and request dedup. Use a server-state library; that problem is solved.

### NN4. Accessibility floor: WCAG 2.2 AA, axe-core in CI

- All routes pass `axe-core` (zero violations) before merge. Block PRs on regressions.
- Manual screen-reader pass on the four primary user flows before any release.
- All interactive elements keyboard-reachable; tab order makes sense.
- Color contrast: 4.5:1 for text under 18pt, 3:1 above.
- Forms: labels, programmatically marked required fields, errors announced.

Tooling: `axe-core` + `@axe-core/playwright` (or `cypress-axe`) for component / E2E; `eslint-plugin-jsx-a11y` (or `eslint-plugin-vuejs-accessibility`) for component lint; Lighthouse a11y score >= 95 for marketing pages.

### NN5. Core Web Vitals targets (75th percentile, real users)

| Metric | Target | What it measures |
|---|---|---|
| **LCP** (Largest Contentful Paint) | < 2.5s | When the main content is visible |
| **INP** (Interaction to Next Paint) | < 200ms | Responsiveness to user input |
| **CLS** (Cumulative Layout Shift) | < 0.1 | Visual stability |

Measure with **RUM** (real user monitoring): `web-vitals` library + your analytics. Lab-only (Lighthouse in CI) misses real-world variance. Set CI gates on lab numbers as a floor; RUM is the truth.

### NN6. Testing pyramid for frontend

| Layer | Tool | What it catches |
|---|---|---|
| **Unit** (most) | Vitest / Jest | Pure functions, utils, reducers, hooks in isolation |
| **Component** | Testing Library (RTL / Vue / Svelte) | Component behavior from user POV (clicks, accessibility queries, render output) |
| **E2E** (fewest) | Playwright / Cypress | Critical user flows end-to-end (sign-in, checkout, primary feature) |
| **Visual regression** (opt-in) | Chromatic / Percy / Playwright snapshots | Styling drift on a small, intentionally selected surface |

Avoid: snapshot tests of entire components (brittle, noisy); E2E for things a component test could cover (slow, flaky).

### NN7. Supply-chain + security defaults

- **CSP** (Content Security Policy) header: `default-src 'self'` minimum; explicitly allow what you actually need; reject inline scripts.
- **SRI** (Subresource Integrity) hashes for any CDN-loaded script you do not control.
- **Dependency scanning in CI**: `npm audit` (or `pnpm audit` / `yarn audit`), `dependabot` or Renovate enabled, block on Critical/High CVEs.
- **No unverified `npx` in build steps.** Pin package versions; CI verifies the lockfile.
- **COOP / COEP** only if you actually need `SharedArrayBuffer` or isolation; otherwise skip and don't break embedded content (Stripe, YouTube, etc.).
- **No secrets in client bundles.** Build-time env vars with public names (`PUBLIC_*` / `VITE_*` / `NEXT_PUBLIC_*`) are **baked into the bundle**. Secrets stay server-side.

